  "prompt": "How do you calculate credit hours earned?",
  "response": "Calculating credit hours earned can vary depending on the educational institution and the specific structure of its courses. However, the general approach involves the following steps:\n\n1. **Identify the Courses:**\n   - List all the courses you have completed within the relevant term or academic period.\n\n2. **Determine the Credit Hours Per Course:**\n   - Each course has a specified number of credit hours associated with it. This information is usually available in the course catalog or syllabus. Typically, one credit hour corresponds to approximately one hour of class time per week over a standard term.\n\n3. **Sum the Credit Hours:**\n   - Add up the credit hours of all the courses you have completed successfully. \n\nFor example, if you completed three courses in a semester with the following credit hours: \n\n- Course 1: 3 credit hours\n- Course 2: 4 credit hours\n- Course 3: 2 credit hours\n\nYour total credit hours earned for that semester would be:\n\n3 + 4 + 2 = 9 credit hours\n\n### Additional Considerations\n\n- **Passing Grades:**\n  - Ensure that you have received passing grades in these courses, as failing a course may mean you do not earn the credit hours associated with it.\n\n- **Transfer Credits:**\n  - If you have transfer credits from another institution, these may be added to your total credit hours earned, subject to the acceptance policy of your current institution.\n\n- **Lab/Practical Courses:**\n  - Some courses with laboratory or practical components may have different credit hour calculations, often combining both lecture hours and lab hours.\n\n### Specific Cases\n\nSome institutions might have more specific policies regarding credit hour calculations, particularly for courses involving labs, internships, or other practical components. Always refer to your institution\u2019s guidelines for precise calculations.\n\nAlways refer to your academic advisor or registrar\u2019s office for confirmation and to ensure you are accounting for all relevant details.",
